Example.Name: Single-Point Thermocouple Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking single readings from up to four thermocouples.

Example.Name: Continuous Thermocouple Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking continuous readings from up to four thermocouples.

Example.Name: Single-Point Thermistor Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking single readings from up to four thermistors.

Example.Name: Continuous Thermistor Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking continuous readings from up to four thermistors.

Example.Name: Single-Point RTD Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking single readings from up to four RTDs.

Example.Name: Continuous RTD Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking continuous readings from up to four RTDs.

Example.Name: Single-Point Strain Gauge Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking single readings from up to four strain gauges.

Example.Name: Continuous Strain Gauge Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking continuous readings from up to four strain gauges.

Example.Name: 1 Channel Oscilloscope
Example.Description: Simple 1 Channel Oscilloscope with very basic functionality.

Example.Name: 2 Channel Oscilloscope
Example.Description: A simple 2 channel oscilloscope with features such as triggering.

Example.Name: Digital Multimeter
Example.Description: A simple digital multimeter example which can take AC and DC voltage measurements.

Example.Name: Function Generator
Example.Description: A simple function generator example which can output sine, square, sawtooth, and triangle waveforms.

Example.Name: Arbitrary Waveform Generator
Example.Description: An arbitrary waveform generator where you can create, edit, save, load and output waveforms on up to two channels.

Example.Name: Spectrum Analyzer
Example.Description:
A simple spectrum analyzer example which shows the peak power, peak frequency, and the frequency spectrum using a variety of time-domain windows.
This example requires the LabVIEW Advanced Analysis package to be installed.

Example.Name: Single-Point Voltage Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking single voltage readings from any source you connect to an analog input channel.

Example.Name: Continuous Voltage Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking continuous voltage readings from any source you connect to analog input channels.

Example.Name: Single-Point Current Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking single current readings from any source you connect to an analog input channel.

Example.Name: Continuous Current Measurement
Example.Description: A solution for taking continuous current readings from any source you connect to analog input channels.

Example.Name: Simple Data Logger
Example.Description: A simple software timed data logger which receives data from any source you connect to analog input channels. Time and date stamped data are logged to a spreadsheet format file.

Example.Name: Simple Data Reader
Example.Description: An example of retrieving and displaying logged data from the data file generated with the Simple Data Logger.

Example.Name: Advanced Data Logger
Example.Description: A software timed advanced data logger which receives data from any source you connect to analog input channels. Time and date stamped data are logged to a spreadsheet format file along with header information.

Example.Name: Advanced Data Reader
Example.Description: An example of retrieving and displaying logged data from the data file generated with the Advanced Data Logger.

Example.Name: High Speed Data Logger
Example.Description: A high speed, hardware timed, data logger which receives data from any source you connect to analog input channels. Data is logged to a binary file.

Example.Name: High Speed Data Reader
Example.Description: An example of retrieving and displaying logged data from the data file generated with the High Speed Data Logger.

Example.Name: PID Control Demo
Example.Description: A PID example demo which does not require an external system to control. You can choose from first order or second order internal software systems.

Example.Name: PID Control Loop
Example.Description: A PID example you can use to control your own external system. The process variable of your system will be read as an analog input, and the PID output to your system will be generated as an analog output.

Example.Name: Real-Time (E series) PID Control Loop
Example.Description: A real-time PID example you can use to control your own external system. The process variable of your system will be read as an analog input, and the PID output to your system will be generated as an analog output. The input and output are synchronized with hardware timing.

Example.Name: Alarm Controller
Example.Description: An alarm controller which monitors analog input channels and sets digital lines if alarm states occur. You can choose high, low, low-to-high, or high-to-low limit alarms.
